# GitHub Actions: Security

## Secret management

- Store all sensitive values in GitHub Secrets (repo, org, or environment). Never hardcode, never echo.
- Access via `${{ secrets.MY_SECRET }}`; use environment-level secrets for deployment envs with approval rules.
- GitHub masks secrets in logs, but still avoid printing them directly or constructing them dynamically in shell.
- Minimize scope: only grant access to the jobs/environments that need a given secret.

### Example — environment secret with approval

```yaml
jobs:
  deploy:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    environment:
      name: production
      url: https://prod.example.com
    steps:
      - name: Deploy to production
        env:
          PROD_API_KEY: ${{ secrets.PROD_API_KEY }}
        run: ./deploy-script.sh
```

## OIDC for cloud authentication

- Use OpenID Connect (OIDC) to exchange a short-lived JWT for temporary cloud credentials — no long-lived access keys stored as secrets.
- Configure trust policies in AWS (IAM roles), Azure (AD app registrations), or GCP (service accounts) to trust GitHub's OIDC issuer.
- Use the provider's official action (e.g. `aws-actions/configure-aws-credentials@<SHA> # v4.x.x`), pinned to a full commit SHA.
- Strongly prefer OIDC over storing cloud credentials for any new workflow.

## Least privilege for `GITHUB_TOKEN`

- Set `permissions:` explicitly. Default to `contents: read`; add write permissions only where strictly required.
- Override at the job level when a single job needs elevated privileges.

### Example

```yaml
permissions:
  contents: read        # default, explicit
  pull-requests: write  # only if workflow updates PRs
  checks: write         # only if workflow publishes check runs

jobs:
  lint:
    permissions:
      contents: read    # job override: this one only reads
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@34e114876b0b11c390a56381ad16ebd13914f8d5 # v4.3.1
      - run: npm run lint
```

## Dependency review and SCA

- Integrate SCA tooling early in CI: `dependency-review-action` (GitHub), Snyk, Trivy, or Mend.
- Set up alerts for new vulnerabilities in transitive dependencies.
- Keep dependency manifests (`package-lock.json`, `requirements.txt`, etc.) committed and up to date.

## SAST

- Integrate static analysis: CodeQL (GitHub Advanced Security), SonarQube, Bandit (Python), ESLint security plugins (JS/TS).
- Configure SAST to fail builds or block PRs on critical findings.
- Run SAST as part of the PR pipeline so developers see issues pre-merge.

## Secret scanning and leak prevention

- Enable GitHub's built-in secret scanning for the repository.
- Recommend pre-commit hooks (e.g. `git-secrets`) for local prevention.
- Pass secrets only at runtime — never bake them into build artifacts or Docker images.

## Image signing and immutable infrastructure

- Ensure reproducible builds (pinned base images, pinned dependency versions).
- Sign container images with Cosign or Notary; verify signatures during deploy.
- Enforce deployment gates that only allow signed, attested images to reach production.

## Security review checklist

- [ ] All secrets accessed via `${{ secrets.* }}`; none hardcoded.
- [ ] OIDC used for cloud authentication where supported.
- [ ] `permissions:` explicitly defined and minimal.
- [ ] Dependency review / SCA integrated in CI.
- [ ] SAST integrated and blocking on critical findings.
- [ ] Secret scanning enabled; pre-commit hooks recommended.
- [ ] Container images signed and verified at deploy time (if applicable).
- [ ] Self-hosted runners (if any) are hardened and network-restricted.
